## § 9 — Retweet (Batch from Feed)

Retweet multiple tweets from the feed in a SINGLE evaluate. No per-tweet navigation needed.
Replace `${targetUrls}` with a JSON array of href paths (e.g. `["/user/status/123"]`).

```bash
exec curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3847/api/browser/{{browser_profile}}/evaluate -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d @- <<'ENDJSON'
{"fn":"async () => { const targetUrls = ${targetUrls}; const tweets = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('article[data-testid=\"tweet\"]')); const results = []; for (const url of targetUrls) { const target = tweets.find(t => { const link = t.querySelector('a[href*=\"/status/\"]'); return link && link.getAttribute('href') === url; }); if (!target) { results.push({ url, error: 'not found' }); continue; } const btn = target.querySelector('[data-testid=\"retweet\"]'); if (!btn) { results.push({ url, already: !!target.querySelector('[data-testid=\"unretweet\"]') }); continue; } btn.click(); await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 1000)); const items = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('[role=\"menuitem\"]')); const repostBtn = items.find(i => i.innerText.includes('Repost')); if (!repostBtn) { results.push({ url, error: 'no repost option' }); continue; } repostBtn.click(); await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 1500)); results.push({ url, retweeted: !!target.querySelector('[data-testid=\"unretweet\"]') }); } return { results, count: results.filter(r => r.retweeted).length }; }"}
ENDJSON
```

Returns `{ results: [...], count: N }`. Each result has `url` + `retweeted: true/false`.
🚨 Do NOT navigate to individual tweets for retweeting — batch from feed is 1 step instead of 21.

## § 10 — Thread (Hook-then-Reply)

🚨 **NEVER use the multi-textarea thread composer** — it is broken. The hook-then-reply approach is the ONLY supported thread method.

### Pattern: post hook → navigate to it → reply sequentially

**Step 1 — Post hook tweet via compose dialog (§ 7 pattern)**

**Step 2 — Get hook tweet URL from profile:**
```bash
exec curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3847/api/browser/{{browser_profile}}/navigate -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"url":"https://x.com/{{handle_slug}}"}' 2>&1

exec curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3847/api/browser/{{browser_profile}}/evaluate -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d @- <<'ENDJSON'
{"fn":"async () => { await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 2000)); const articles = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('article[data-testid=\"tweet\"]')); const first = articles[0]; if (!first) return { error: 'no tweets' }; const link = first.querySelector('a[href*=\"/status/\"]'); const text = (first.querySelector('[data-testid=\"tweetText\"]') || {}).innerText?.slice(0, 80) || ''; return { url: link ? 'https://x.com' + link.getAttribute('href') : '', text }; }"}
ENDJSON
```

**Step 3 — Reply chain (repeat for each body tweet + CTA):**
Navigate to hook tweet URL, then use BROWSER-core.md § 1 reply evaluate (clipboard paste + click submit). Verify via evaluate that articles contain @{{handle_slug}} reply.

For tweet 3+: navigate to the PREVIOUS reply URL (not the hook), so the chain stays linear.
Get each reply URL after posting:
```bash
exec curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3847/api/browser/{{browser_profile}}/evaluate -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d @- <<'ENDJSON'
{"fn":"async () => { await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 1500)); const articles = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('article[data-testid=\"tweet\"]')); const ours = articles.filter(a => { const h = (a.querySelector('[data-testid=\"User-Name\"]') || {}).innerText?.split(String.fromCharCode(10)).find(l => l.startsWith('@')); return h === '@{{handle_slug}}'; }); const latest = ours[ours.length - 1]; const link = latest?.querySelector('a[href*=\"/status/\"]'); return { count: ours.length, latestUrl: link ? 'https://x.com' + link.getAttribute('href') : '' }; }"}
ENDJSON
```

### Cost: ~18 steps for 5-tweet thread (~$1.00) vs 68 steps with broken composer (~$9.00).

